vibe: 2.0

meta:
  name: vibe_v2_mcp_server
  description: >
    Local MCP server architecture for VIBE v2. Defines tools, prompts,
    resources, session management, and Docker deployment. Detailed enough
    to build directly from.
  session_id: 2026-03-10-a7f3b2
  created_at: "2026-03-10"
  author: claude
  tags:
    - mcp
    - server
    - architecture
    - v2
  status: draft

imports:
  - plans/00_vision.vibe
  - plans/50_session_system.vibe

context:
  problem: |
    VIBE v2 documents need to be created and managed by AI systems during
    planning sessions. MCP (Model Context Protocol) provides a standard
    interface for AI tools to interact with external systems. A local MCP
    server gives AI systems the ability to create, read, and manage .vibe
    planning documents within tracked sessions.

  constraints: |
    - Must run locally only (no cloud deployment)
    - Must be Docker-contained for easy setup
    - Must use the official Python mcp SDK
    - Must use stdio transport (standard for local MCP servers)
    - Must not require external databases or services
    - Session storage must persist across server restarts

  assumptions: |
    - MCP-compatible clients (Claude Desktop, Cursor, etc.) are the primary consumers
    - Python 3.12+ is the implementation language
    - Docker is available on developer machines
    - File system is the storage backend (no database needed)
    - One session directory per planning session, no cross-session locking

  scope: |
    Covers MCP server architecture, tools, prompts, and resources.
    Session ID format and lifecycle are in 50_session_system.vibe.
    Does not cover deployment to cloud or multi-user scenarios.

  glossary: |
    - MCP: Model Context Protocol -- standard for AI tool integration
    - MCP Tool: A function an AI can call (like create_session, write_plan)
    - MCP Prompt: A system prompt template the AI can request
    - MCP Resource: Static content the AI can read (like specs, templates)
    - stdio transport: Communication over stdin/stdout (standard for local MCP)

artifacts:
  - path: mcp-server/Dockerfile
    kind: dockerfile
    description: Docker image definition for the MCP server
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Based on python:3.12-slim
      - Installs dependencies from pyproject.toml
      - Sets stdio as the transport mechanism
      - Mounts session storage and spec volumes

  - path: mcp-server/docker-compose.yml
    kind: yaml
    description: Docker Compose configuration for easy local deployment
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Single service definition
      - Volume mounts for session storage and VIBE spec/stdlib
      - Spec/stdlib mounted read-only
      - Works with docker compose up

  - path: mcp-server/pyproject.toml
    kind: toml
    description: Python project configuration with dependencies
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Requires Python 3.12+
      - Depends on mcp SDK, pyyaml, jsonschema
      - Defines entry point for the MCP server

  - path: mcp-server/src/server.py
    kind: python
    description: MCP server entry point with stdio transport
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Registers all tools, prompts, and resources
      - Uses stdio transport
      - Handles graceful shutdown

  - path: mcp-server/src/tools/session_tools.py
    kind: python
    description: MCP tools for session management
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Implements create_session, list_sessions, get_session, archive_session
      - All tools return structured JSON responses

  - path: mcp-server/src/tools/plan_tools.py
    kind: python
    description: MCP tools for plan document management
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Implements write_plan and read_plan
      - write_plan validates YAML and v2 schema before writing
      - read_plan returns parsed YAML content

  - path: mcp-server/src/session/manager.py
    kind: python
    description: Session lifecycle management
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Creates session directories under data/sessions/
      - Generates session.json metadata
      - Supports archiving (move to data/archive/)

  - path: mcp-server/src/session/id_gen.py
    kind: python
    description: Session ID generation
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Generates IDs in format {YYYY-MM-DD}-{6-char-hex}
      - IDs are unique (hex portion from os.urandom)

  - path: mcp-server/src/validation/schema.py
    kind: python
    description: VIBE v2 schema validation
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Validates .vibe files against vibe.schema.json
      - Returns structured error messages
      - Handles missing optional fields gracefully

  - path: mcp-server/src/prompts/plan_in_vibe.py
    kind: python
    description: MCP prompt that instructs AI to output in .vibe format
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Returns a system prompt with v2 format specification
      - Includes section type reference
      - Includes example document structure

  - path: mcp-server/src/resources/spec.py
    kind: python
    description: MCP resources exposing spec and templates
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Exposes VIBE spec documents as readable resources
      - Exposes stdlib templates as readable resources
      - Resources are read-only

sections:
  - id: architecture_overview
    type: design
    title: Architecture Overview
    content: |
      The MCP server is a Python application that runs locally inside Docker.
      It communicates with AI clients via stdio transport (stdin/stdout).

      Directory structure:
        mcp-server/
          Dockerfile
          docker-compose.yml
          pyproject.toml
          src/
            __init__.py
            server.py               # MCP server entry, stdio transport
            tools/
              __init__.py
              session_tools.py      # create_session, list_sessions, get_session, archive_session
              plan_tools.py         # write_plan, read_plan
            session/
              __init__.py
              manager.py            # Session lifecycle
              id_gen.py             # ID generation ({date}-{hex})
            validation/
              __init__.py
              schema.py             # VIBE v2 schema validation
            prompts/
              __init__.py
              plan_in_vibe.py       # System prompt for .vibe output
            resources/
              __init__.py
              spec.py               # Spec + templates as MCP resources
          data/sessions/            # Default storage mount point

      Data flow:
        AI Client <--stdio--> MCP Server <--filesystem--> Session Storage
                                          <--filesystem--> VIBE Spec (read-only)

  - id: mcp_tools
    type: specification
    title: MCP Tool Definitions
    content: |
      Six tools are exposed to AI clients:

      ### create_session
      Creates a new planning session.
      Parameters:
        - name: string (required) -- Human-readable session name
        - description: string (optional) -- What this session is about
        - tags: string[] (optional) -- Categorization tags
      Returns:
        - session_id: string -- Generated session ID
        - path: string -- Absolute path to session directory
        - created_at: string -- ISO datetime
      Behavior:
        1. Generate session ID via id_gen
        2. Create directory data/sessions/{session_id}/
        3. Write session.json with metadata
        4. Return session info

      ### write_plan
      Creates or updates a .vibe plan document within a session.
      Parameters:
        - session_id: string (required) -- Target session
        - filename: string (required) -- Filename (must end in .vibe)
        - content: string (required) -- YAML content of the .vibe file
      Returns:
        - path: string -- Absolute path to written file
        - valid: boolean -- Whether content passed schema validation
        - errors: string[] -- Validation errors (if any, still writes file)
      Behavior:
        1. Verify session exists
        2. Parse content as YAML
        3. Validate against v2 schema (warn on failure, don't block)
        4. Write to data/sessions/{session_id}/{filename}
        5. Update session.json last_modified
        6. Return result with validation status

      ### read_plan
      Reads a .vibe plan document from a session.
      Parameters:
        - session_id: string (required) -- Target session
        - filename: string (required) -- Filename to read
      Returns:
        - content: string -- Raw YAML content
        - parsed: object -- Parsed YAML as JSON
        - valid: boolean -- Schema validation status
      Behavior:
        1. Verify session and file exist
        2. Read and parse YAML
        3. Validate against schema
        4. Return content in both raw and parsed forms

      ### list_sessions
      Lists all active sessions.
      Parameters:
        - tag: string (optional) -- Filter by tag
        - status: string (optional) -- Filter by session status
      Returns:
        - sessions: array of {session_id, name, created_at, file_count, status}
      Behavior:
        1. Scan data/sessions/ directory
        2. Read session.json from each
        3. Apply filters
        4. Return sorted by created_at descending

      ### get_session
      Gets detailed information about a session.
      Parameters:
        - session_id: string (required) -- Target session
      Returns:
        - session_id, name, description, tags, created_at, status
        - files: array of {filename, created_at, modified_at, meta}
      Behavior:
        1. Read session.json
        2. List all .vibe files in session directory
        3. Read meta from each file
        4. Return aggregated info

      ### archive_session
      Moves a session to archive storage.
      Parameters:
        - session_id: string (required) -- Target session
      Returns:
        - archived: boolean
        - archive_path: string
      Behavior:
        1. Verify session exists
        2. Move directory to data/archive/{session_id}/
        3. Update session.json status to "archived"
        4. Return result

  - id: mcp_prompts
    type: specification
    title: MCP Prompt Definitions
    content: |
      One prompt is exposed:

      ### plan_in_vibe
      Instructs the AI to produce output in .vibe v2 format.
      Arguments:
        - document_type: string (optional) -- Archetype hint (overview,
          architecture, implementation_plan, risk_assessment, adr_collection)
        - session_id: string (optional) -- Session to write into
      Returns system prompt containing:
        1. VIBE v2 format specification (condensed)
        2. Section type reference
        3. Document archetype guidance (if document_type provided)
        4. Example document skeleton
        5. Session context (if session_id provided, includes existing plans)
        6. Instructions to use write_plan tool for output

      This prompt is the primary way AI systems learn the .vibe format
      within a conversation. It should be concise but complete enough
      for the AI to produce valid documents without reading the full spec.

  - id: mcp_resources
    type: specification
    title: MCP Resource Definitions
    content: |
      Resources are read-only content the AI can request:

      ### vibe://spec/v2
      The full VIBE v2 specification document.
      MIME type: text/markdown

      ### vibe://spec/format
      Condensed format reference (field definitions only).
      MIME type: text/yaml

      ### vibe://templates/{archetype}
      Document templates for each archetype:
        - vibe://templates/overview
        - vibe://templates/architecture
        - vibe://templates/implementation_plan
        - vibe://templates/risk_assessment
        - vibe://templates/adr_collection
      MIME type: text/yaml

      ### vibe://stdlib/quality
      The quality criteria library.
      MIME type: text/yaml

  - id: docker_setup
    type: specification
    title: Docker Configuration
    content: |
      ### Dockerfile
        FROM python:3.12-slim
        WORKDIR /app
        COPY pyproject.toml .
        RUN pip install -e .
        COPY src/ src/
        CMD ["python", "-m", "src.server"]

      ### docker-compose.yml
        services:
          vibe-mcp:
            build: .
            stdin_open: true
            volumes:
              - ./data/sessions:/app/data/sessions
              - ../vibe/spec:/app/vibe/spec:ro
              - ../vibe/stdlib:/app/vibe/stdlib:ro
              - ../vibe/schema:/app/vibe/schema:ro

      The server uses stdio transport, so stdin_open: true is required.
      Session data is persisted via volume mount. Spec and stdlib are
      mounted read-only so the server can expose them as MCP resources.

      ### pyproject.toml
        [project]
        name = "vibe-mcp-server"
        version = "0.1.0"
        requires-python = ">=3.12"
        dependencies = [
            "mcp>=1.0",
            "pyyaml>=6.0",
            "jsonschema>=4.20",
        ]

        [project.scripts]
        vibe-mcp = "src.server:main"

  - id: server_entry
    type: specification
    title: Server Entry Point Design
    content: |
      src/server.py is the main entry point:

        import asyncio
        from mcp.server import Server
        from mcp.server.stdio import stdio_server

        from src.tools.session_tools import register_session_tools
        from src.tools.plan_tools import register_plan_tools
        from src.prompts.plan_in_vibe import register_prompts
        from src.resources.spec import register_resources

        app = Server("vibe-mcp-server")

        register_session_tools(app)
        register_plan_tools(app)
        register_prompts(app)
        register_resources(app)

        async def main():
            async with stdio_server() as (read_stream, write_stream):
                await app.run(read_stream, write_stream)

        if __name__ == "__main__":
            asyncio.run(main())

      Each registration function uses the @app.tool(), @app.prompt(),
      and @app.resource() decorators from the mcp SDK.

  - id: validation_design
    type: design
    title: Schema Validation Approach
    content: |
      src/validation/schema.py provides v2 schema validation:

      1. Load vibe/schema/vibe.schema.json at startup
      2. On write_plan, parse YAML to dict, validate against schema
      3. Validation is advisory: write_plan still writes on failure
         but returns errors in the response
      4. This lets AI systems iterate on content without being blocked

      Validation checks:
      - Required field: vibe (must be 2.0)
      - Field types: meta is object, sections is array, etc.
      - Enum values: section.type in [analysis, design, decision,
        specification, risk, checklist]
      - Enum values: meta.status in [draft, review, final]
      - Enum values: decision.status in [proposed, accepted,
        deprecated, superseded]

  - id: error_handling
    type: design
    title: Error Handling
    content: |
      MCP tool errors follow MCP SDK conventions:

      - Session not found: return error with message, don't throw
      - File not found: return error with message
      - Invalid YAML: return error with parse error details
      - Schema validation failure: return warnings (not errors),
        still complete the operation
      - Filesystem errors: return error with OS error message

      All tools return structured JSON. Errors include:
        { "error": true, "message": "...", "code": "SESSION_NOT_FOUND" }

      Error codes: SESSION_NOT_FOUND, FILE_NOT_FOUND, INVALID_YAML,
      SCHEMA_VALIDATION_FAILED, FILESYSTEM_ERROR

decisions:
  - id: dec_python
    title: Use Python for MCP server implementation
    status: proposed
    context: |
      The MCP server needs a language with good MCP SDK support,
      YAML parsing, and JSON Schema validation.
    options:
      - name: python
        description: Python with official mcp SDK, pyyaml, jsonschema
      - name: typescript
        description: TypeScript with @modelcontextprotocol/sdk, js-yaml
      - name: go
        description: Go with community MCP libraries
    chosen: python
    rationale: |
      Python has the official mcp SDK with the most complete feature
      set. pyyaml and jsonschema are battle-tested. Python is also
      the most common language for AI tooling, making contributions
      easier.
    consequences:
      - Requires Python 3.12+ runtime (provided by Docker)
      - No compilation step needed
      - Straightforward async with asyncio

  - id: dec_stdio
    title: Use stdio transport (not HTTP/SSE)
    status: proposed
    context: |
      MCP supports multiple transports. stdio is the simplest for
      local-only servers.
    options:
      - name: stdio
        description: Communication over stdin/stdout, standard for local MCP
      - name: sse
        description: HTTP with Server-Sent Events, standard for remote MCP
    chosen: stdio
    rationale: |
      stdio is the standard transport for local MCP servers. It requires
      no port management, no HTTP server, and works naturally with Docker.
      SSE is for remote servers which is out of scope for v2.
    consequences:
      - Docker needs stdin_open: true
      - No web UI or HTTP API (intentional)
      - MCP clients connect via command execution

  - id: dec_advisory_validation
    title: Schema validation is advisory (doesn't block writes)
    status: proposed
    context: |
      Should write_plan reject documents that fail schema validation?
    options:
      - name: strict
        description: Reject writes that fail schema validation
      - name: advisory
        description: Write the file but return validation warnings
    chosen: advisory
    rationale: |
      AI systems iterate on content. Blocking writes on validation
      failures forces the AI to fix all issues before saving, which
      breaks the natural flow of iterative planning. Advisory
      validation lets the AI save work-in-progress and fix issues
      in subsequent calls.
    consequences:
      - write_plan always succeeds (unless filesystem error)
      - Validation errors returned in response for AI to address
      - AI can choose to fix issues or accept them

quality:
  - id: q_tools_complete
    type: review
    description: All MCP tools are fully specified
    criteria: |
      - Each tool has parameters, return type, and behavior documented
      - Error cases are enumerated
      - No ambiguity in tool behavior

  - id: q_buildable
    type: review
    description: Architecture is detailed enough to implement directly
    criteria: |
      - Directory structure is complete
      - File purposes are clear
      - Key code patterns are shown (server entry, tool registration)
      - Docker configuration is complete
      - Dependency versions are specified

  - id: q_mcp_compliant
    type: test
    description: Server follows MCP protocol correctly
    criteria: |
      - Uses official mcp Python SDK
      - Tools, prompts, and resources follow MCP schema conventions
      - stdio transport is correctly configured
      - Responses are valid MCP response objects
